05089nam a22007455i 9789814414517DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2013    si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898144145177 a10.1355/97898144145172doi  a(DE-B1597)492417  a(OCoLC)1041986395  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 4aDS33bAsi 2013 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a95022300aAsia Redux :bConceptualizing a Region for Our Times /cPrasenjit Duara. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface / rBose, Sugata -- tIntroduction / rMunger, Jennifer -- tAsia Redux: Conceptualizing a Region for Our Times / rDuara, Prasenjit -- tThe Idea of Asia and Its Ambiguities / rHui, Wang -- tThe Intricacies of Premodern Asian Connections / rSen, Tansen -- tAsia Is Not One / rAcharya, Amitav -- tResponse to Prasenjit Duara, "Asia Redux" / rAndaya, Barbara Watson -- tfloating. No Gears Shifting / rMrázek, Rudolf -- tResponse to Comments on "Asia Redux" / rDuara, Prasenjit -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"In the erudite essay that opens this forum, Prasenjit Duara turns to both indigenous thinkers and the premodern past for tools with which to think about Asia in a global age. Contemporary modalities of regional exchange - 'weakly bounded, network-oriented, pluralistic, multitemporal' - chime with earlier patterns of cultural circulation without state domination, giving rise to a prophetic vision of 'Asia Redux'. This attempt to capture the contours of a (re)-emergent region was calculated to provide. And what a debate it kicks off. Wang Hui resolutely reframe imagining Asia as a political project on a world-historical canvas. Tansen Sen greatly complicates the map of intra-Asian commercial exchange in earlier times; Amitav Acharya outlines five competing conceptions of Asia in the domain of international relations alone.; Barbara Watson Andaya teases out the paradoxical way in which regional religions make clashing claims about Asian unity; and Rudolf Mrazek asks, what of the Asia that bleeds? what of exploitation and its spawn, the inglorious 'built-ends' of the global economy? The reward for those who read this collection straight through is a thrillingly cacophonous conversation about how to grasp Asia in our time." - Karen E. Wigen, Stanford University "Will a re-emergent Asia extend the violent rivalries and inequalities of Western-dominated empires, nations and capital? Or can Asia somehow draw on a relatively more peaceful past of maritime trade, interlinked religions and circulations beyond states to think and make a very different sort of region and world? Prasenjit Duara and his interlocutors define this vital debate on Asia's future through illuminating reflections on its recent and deep past. A touchstone for anyone concerned with a future shape of an inter-connected Asia newly possessed of wealth and power" - Engseng Ho, Duke University  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aDuara, Prasenjit, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Publishing ebook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060668308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066300640uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/9789814414517423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814414517.jpg  a978-3-11-060668-3  ISEAS Publishing ebook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec200